Provides(x, y, z) ::: x provides y to z.
FinancialAid(x) ::: x is financial aid.
Applicant(x) ::: x is an applicant.
GREApplicant(x) ::: x is a GRE applicant.
Prove(x, y) ::: x proves y.
EconomicHardship(x) ::: x is economic hardship.
RefersTo(x, y) ::: x refers to y.
Difficulty(x) ::: x is a difficulty.
CausedBy(x, y) ::: x is caused by y.
HavingTooLittleMoney(x) ::: x is having too little money.
HavingTooFewResources(x) ::: x is having too few resources.
LivesIn(x, y) ::: x lives in y.
SingleParentFamily(x) ::: x is a single-parent family.
Person(x) ::: x is a person.
Dad(x, y) ::: x is the dad of y.
OutOfWork(x, y) ::: x has been out of work for y.
Year(x) ::: x is a year.
Tom(x) ::: x is Tom.

# Premises:
# General cost and provision of financial aid
Cost(GRE, 205USD).
∀x (GREApplicant(x) ∧ Prove(x, EconomicHardship) → Provides(ETS, FinancialAid, x)).

# Definition of Economic Hardship
∀eh (EconomicHardship(eh) ↔ (Difficulty(eh) ∧ (CausedBy(eh, HavingTooLittleMoney) ∨ CausedBy(eh, HavingTooFewResources)))).

# Tom's situation
Tom(tom).
Person(tom).
LivesIn(tom, SingleParentFamily).
Dad(dad_of_tom, tom).
Person(dad_of_tom).
OutOfWork(dad_of_tom, MoreThanOneYear).

# Specific instances and their types
SingleParentFamily(single_parent_family).
MoreThanOneYear(more_than_one_year).
Applicant(tom).
GREApplicant(tom).
FinancialAid(financial_aid).
ETS(ets).

# Economic hardship is defined as a difficulty.
# This is a refinement of the definition, linking Difficulty to EconomicHardship directly.
∀eh (EconomicHardship(eh) → Difficulty(eh)).

# The situation of living in a single-parent family with an unemployed father is a cause of difficulty.
# This implies having too little money or resources.
∀t (LivesIn(t, SingleParentFamily) → CausedBy(Difficulty_DueToFamily(t), HavingTooLittleMoney)).
∀d (OutOfWork(d, MoreThanOneYear) → CausedBy(Difficulty_DueToUnemployment(d), HavingTooFewResources)).

# Tom's specific difficulties
Difficulty_DueToFamily(tom).
Difficulty_DueToUnemployment(dad_of_tom).

# Establishing EconomicHardship for Tom
# If Tom faces difficulty due to family situation, and this difficulty is caused by lack of money/resources,
# then Tom has economic hardship.
∀t (LivesIn(t, SingleParentFamily) ∧ CausedBy(Difficulty_DueToFamily(t), HavingTooLittleMoney) → EconomicHardship(hardship_tom_family_situation)).
# If Tom's dad has been out of work for more than a year, causing difficulty, and this is due to lack of resources,
# then Tom has economic hardship.
∀t (Dad(d, t) ∧ OutOfWork(d, MoreThanOneYear) ∧ CausedBy(Difficulty_DueToUnemployment(d), HavingTooFewResources) → EconomicHardship(hardship_tom_dad_situation)).

# Tom has economic hardship if either of the above conditions are met.
EconomicHardship(hardship_tom_family_situation).
EconomicHardship(hardship_tom_dad_situation).

# For the purpose of the rule, we need a single instance of EconomicHardship that Tom can prove.
# We can represent Tom's overall economic hardship as a distinct entity that encompasses the specific causes.
# This avoids redundancy if multiple hardship conditions lead to the same aid.
EconomicHardship(tom_overall_hardship).
IsCausedBy(tom_overall_hardship, hardship_tom_family_situation).
IsCausedBy(tom_overall_hardship, hardship_tom_dad_situation).

# Tom can prove his overall economic hardship.
Prove(tom, tom_overall_hardship).

# Conclusion:
¬∃x (Applicant(x) ∧ GRE(x) ∧ Provides(ETS, FinancialAid, x))
